<div class="markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert dark"><h3 data-start="0" data-end="47"><strong data-start="4" data-end="45">Myhill-Nerode Theorem in Simple Words</strong></h3><p data-start="49" data-end="324">The <strong data-start="53" data-end="78">Myhill-Nerode theorem</strong> helps us understand whether a language is <strong data-start="121" data-end="132">regular</strong> (i.e., can be recognized by a <strong data-start="163" data-end="191">finite state machine/DFA</strong>). It does this by grouping strings into <strong data-start="232" data-end="255">equivalence classes</strong> based on how they behave when you add extra characters (suffixes).</p><hr data-start="326" data-end="329"><h3 data-start="331" data-end="378"><strong data-start="335" data-end="376">Key Idea: "Indistinguishable Strings"</strong></h3><p data-start="380" data-end="506">Imagine you have a language <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi><br></mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6833em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal">L</span></span></span></span>, and you want to know</p><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6138em; vertical-align: -0.15em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; x</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mrel"><span class="mrel">‚â°</span><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.3283em;"><span style="top: -2.55em; margin-left: 0em; margin-right: 0.05em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 2.7em;"></span><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mght"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">L</span></span></span></span><span class="vlist-s">‚Äã</span></span><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.15em;"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.7194em; vertical-align: -0.1944em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.03588em;">y</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mpunct">,</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 1em;"></span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.1667em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal">x</span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.04398em;">z</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mrel">‚àà</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.7073em; vertical-align: -0.024em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal">pan><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mrel">‚ü∫</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.7335em; vertical-align: -0.1944em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal" style="margin-right: 0.04398em;">yz</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mrel">‚àà</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6833em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal">L</span></span></span><p data-start="380" data-end="506">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;if two strings <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotatincoding="application/x-tex">x</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">y</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;are <strong data-start="477" data-end="491">equivalent</strong> for <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">L</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>.means x ,y lead to same state.</p><p data-start="508" data-end="595">‚úÖ <strong data-start="510" data-end="593">Two strings <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">x</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.o/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">y</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;are equivalent (denoted <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><msub><mo>‚â°</mo><mi>L</mi></msub><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">x \equiv_L y</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>) if:</strong></p><blockquote data-start="596" data-end="755"><p data-start="598" data-end="755">for any string <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">z</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;you add at the end, both <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi><mi>z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">xz</annotation></semantics></math></sn></span>&nbsp;and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>y</mi><mi>z</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">yz</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;<strong data-start="681" data-end="752">either belong to <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">L</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;or don't belong to <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">L</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;in the same way</strong>.</p><p data-start="598" data-end="755">if xz and yz go to same state then so do x and y.</p></blockquote><p data-start="757" data-end="918">In simple words, if you can't tell <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>x</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">x</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">y</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;apart based on their future behavior in <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">L</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>, they <strong data-start="866" data-end="915">must be in the same group (equivalence class)</strong>. classes are nothing but states.</p><hr data-start="920" data-end="923"><h3 data-start="925" data-end="951"><strong data-start="929" data-end="949">The Main Theorem</strong></h3><ol data-start="953" data-end="1155"><li data-start="953" data-end="1068">If a language <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">L</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;is <strong data-start="981" data-end="992">regular</strong>, then there are <strong data-start="1009" data-end="1031">only finitely many</strong> such groups (equivalence classes).</li><li data-start="1069" data-end="1155">If a language has <strong data-start="1090" data-end="1109">infinitely many</strong> such groups, then it <strong data-start="1131" data-end="1152">cannot be regular</strong>.</li></ol><hr data-start="1157" data-end="1160"><h3 data-start="1162" data-end="1201"><strong data-start="1166" data-end="1199">Example 1: A Regular Language</strong></h3><p data-start="1202" data-end="1260">Let‚Äôs say <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mo stretchy="false">{</mo><mi>w</mi><mo>/mo><mi>w</mi><mtext>&nbsp;ends&nbsp;in&nbsp;"01"</mtext><mo stretchy="false">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">L = \{ w \mid w \text{ ends in "01"} \}</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>.</p><p data-start="1262" data-end="1337">Now, let's compare different strings based on their future possibilities:</p><ul data-start="1339" data-end="1617"><li data-start="1339" data-end="1416"><code data-start="1341" data-end="1344">Œµ</code> (empty string) needs <code data-start="1366" data-end="1372">"01"</code> to reach <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6833em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal">L</span></span></span></span> ‚Üí One equivalence class.</li><li data-start="1417" data-end="1477"><code data-start="1419" a-end="1424">"0"</code> still needs <code data-start="1437" data-end="1442">"1"</code> ‚Üí A different equivalence class.</li><li data-start="1478" data-end="1546"><code data-start="1480" data-end="1485">"1"</code> needs <code data-start="1492" data-end="1498">"01"</code> (not just <code data-start="1509" data-end="1514">"1"</code>) ‚Üí Another equivalence class.</li><li data-start="1547" data-end="1617"><code data-start="1549" data-end="1555">"01"</code> is already in <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">L</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6833em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal">L</span></span></span></span> ‚Üí A separate final equivalence class.</li></ul><p data-start="1619" data-end="1689">There are <strong data-start="1629" data-end="1663">only a few equivalence cl/strong> ‚Üí <strong data-start="1666" data-end="1688"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">L</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;is regular</strong>.</p><hr data-start="1691" data-end="1694"><h3 data-start="1696" data-end="1739"><strong data-start="1700" data-end="1737">Example 2: A Non-Regular Language</strong></h3><p data-start="1740" data-end="1837">Take <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mo stretchy="false">{</mo><msup><mi>a</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><msup><mi>b</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>‚à£</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>‚â•</mo><mn>0</mn><mo stretchy="false">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">L = \{ a^n b^n \mid n \geq 0 \}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0m;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal">L</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mrel">=</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 1em; vertical-align: -0.25em;"></span><span class="mopen">{</span><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal">a</span><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.6644em;"><span style="top: -3.063em; margin-right: 0.05em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 2.7em;"></span><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal">b</span><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist" style="height: 0.6644em;"><span style="top: -3.063em; margin-right: 0.05em;"><span class="pstrut" style="height: 2.7em;"></span><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mathnormal mtight">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mrel">‚à£</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.7719em; vertical-align: -0.136em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal">n</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span><span class="mrel">‚â•</span><span class="mspace" style="margin-right: 0.2778em;"></span></span><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 1em; vertical-align: -0.25em;"></span><span class="mord">0</span><span class="mclose">}</span></span></span></span>, which has equal numbers of <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">a</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>‚Äôs and <span class="katex"><span clasex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">b</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>‚Äôs.</p><p data-start="1839" data-end="1872">Now, look at different strings:</p><ul data-start="1874" data-end="2039"><li data-start="1874" data-end="1945"><code data-start="1876" data-end="1881">"a"</code> needs more <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">a</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.4306em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal">a</span></span></span></span>‚Äôs followed by exactly that many <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">b</annotation></semantics></matspan><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="strut" style="height: 0.6944em;"></span><span class="mord mathnormal">b</span></span></span></span>‚Äôs.</li><li data-start="1946" data-end="1983"><code data-start="1948" data-end="1954">"aa"</code> needs even more <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">b</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>‚Äôs.</li><li data-start="1984" data-end="2022"><code data-start="1986" data-end="1993">"aaa"</code> needs even more <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>b</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">b</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>‚Äôs.</li><li data-start="2023" data-end="2039">And so on...</li></ul><p data-start="2041" data-end="2185">Since every different <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">n</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;gives a different behavior, there are <strong data-start="2109" data-end="2148">infinitely many equivalence classes meaning that there are infinitely many states</strong>, meaning <strong data-start="2158" data-end="2184"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow><annotation encoding="application/x-tex">L</annotation></semantics></math></span></span>&nbsp;is not regular</strong>.</p><hr data-start="2187" data-end="2190"><h3 data-start="2192" data-end="2221"><strong data-start="2196" data-end="2219">Why Is This Useful?</strong></h3><ul data-start="2222" data-end="2492"><li data-start="2222" data-end="2307">It gives a <strong data-start="2235" data-end="2255">mathematical way</strong> to prove that some languages are <strong data-start="2289" data-end="2304">not regular</strong>.</li><li data-start="2308" data-end="2402">It is <strong data-start="2316" data-end="2351">stronger than the pumping lemma</strong> (which sometimes fails to prove non-regularity).</li><li data-start="2403" data-end="2492">It helps us design <strong data-start="2424" data-end="2442">efficient DFAs</strong> for regular languages by <strong data-start="2468" data-end="2482">minimizing</strong> states.</li></ul><hr data-start="2494" data-end="2497"><h3 data-start="2499" data-end="2522"><strong data-start="2503" data-end="2520">Final Summary</strong></h3><p data-start="2523" data-end="2618">‚úÖ <strong data-start="2525" data-end="2565">Finite equivalence classes:finite states ‚Üí Regular</strong><br data-start="2565" data-end="2568">‚ùå <strong data-start="2570" data-end="2616">Infinite equivalence classes ‚Üí Not regular</strong></p><p data-start="2620" data-end="2702" data-is-last-node="" data-is-only-node="">Would you like a step-by-step <strong data-start="2650" data-end="2678">DFA minn example</strong> using Myhill-Nerode? üöÄ</p></div>